observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (MDRRMO) to:

a. Evaluate the unutilized balances of the current year’s five per cent LDRRMF, continuing LDRRMF, and the unexpended LDRRMF transferred to the TF books;

b. Anticipate and promptly address issues and concerns affecting the efficient and effective implementation of LDRRM PPAs to avoid delays or non-implementation;

c. Maximize LDRRMF utilization focusing on PPAs requiring the highest priority in terms of urgency and/or impact on the four thematic areas of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management and consider the emerging needs, such as the Corona Virus Disease 2019 and earthquakes; and

d. Ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed and reprogrammed projects during the budget year to optimize the fund’s utilization and warrant that goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities be achieved.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):

Direct Municipal Treasurer (MT) and Municipal Accountant (MA) to obtain from the Authorized Government Depository Bank (AGDB) and the Philippine Health Insurance Corporation (PhilHealth) the necessary information/documents pertaining to the credit and debit memoranda reflected in the bank statements (BS) to facilitate the proper recording in the books of accounts of the Municipality;



Direct the MT to submit immediately DVs and its supporting documents to the Accounting Office for proper recording in the books of accounts and evaluation of the Audit Team on the propriety and validity of the transactions, without prejudice to the issuance of Notices of Suspension/Disallowance/Charge, if warranted; Prospectively, in the release and reporting of the checks issued, the Municipal Treasurer’s Office (MTO) strictly follow the provisions in Sections 42 and 43 of Manual on the New Government Accounting System (MNGAS) for Local Government Units (LGUs);

Direct the MA in coordination with the MTO to review and monitor cancelled checks, cause the replacement for the stale checks, if necessary, provided the stale checks are presented for cancellation and replacement; and

Direct the MT to cancel the unclaimed checks which become invalid after six months and effect adjusting entries for CIB-LCCA and the affected accounts.

We recommended that the LCE: 

Require the conduct physical count of inventory pursuant to Section 124 of the MNGAS for LGUs and submit Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) to the Audit Team for evaluation;
Consider augmentation of inventory committee personnel during the conduct of actual physical count to ensure compliance with the requirements of Section 124 of the MNGAS for LGUs on inventory taking.
Maintain a ledger of all incoming and outgoing supplies/goods;
Maintain a Supplies Ledger Card (SLC) per stock number; and
Reconcile the Inventory Accounts per books with the actual supplies inventory at hand.

We recommended that the LCE:

Direct the concerned offices to hasten the implementation of the partially and unimplemented program, projects and activities (PPAs) under 20 per cent DF to fully attain the desired socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes essential to the promotion of the general welfare of its constituents; 
Adopt a well-defined strategy to enhance the present monitoring and review activities during the planning, procurement, contract implementation and program evaluation phase, in order for the planners and implementers to continuously monitor the timely implementation, so that immediate appropriate and corrective actions could be done on noted gaps along the way; 
Determine the total unobligated balances of completed PPAs and cause the reversion to unappropriated surplus for reprogramming in CY 2022; and

Make an assessment of all PPAs not yet implemented in the current year and prior years continuing to determine whether the funding for such PPAs are necessary, if not then revert to the unappropriated surplus and reprogram to development projects of utmost concern of the Municipality.

We recommended the Management to:

Maintain a ledger of all incoming and outgoing supplies/goods;



Adopt the use of Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) in each issuance of supplies; 


Consolidate the RIS into Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and furnish the Municipal Accountant the same to facilitate the timely and accurate presentation of the inventories on hand in the FS;
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory taking of all the assets of the Municipality of Capalonga, both Property, Plant and Equipment (PPEs) and Supplies Inventory Annually; 



Submit the properly accomplished Report on the Physical Count of Inventory (RPCI) as prescribed by existing regulations to the accounting department and the COA;
Maintain a Supplies Ledger Card (SLC) per stock number; and


Reconcile the Inventory Accounts per books with the actual supplies inventory at hand.

