We recommended the Management to:

Ensure strict monitoring of the contractors’ implementation of the bidded Programs, Projects and Activities (PPAs) against submitted and approved implementation schedules to avoid delay in the completion of the PPAs. In case of noted delays, take necessary and appropriate actions in accordance with existing rules and regulations to timely address these delays;
Ensure that the Accounting Office timely prepare the Obligation Request (ObR) and Budget Office to promptly update the budget records to reflect the proper balances;
When warranted, consider reinforcing the manpower in the Municipal Engineering Office (MEO) by hiring additional engineers to ensure that PPAs targeted under the current year’s 20 per cent DF, as well as the PPAs which remained not fully implemented in the continuing prior years’ 20 per cent DF, are not overlooked and were given priority in the implementation since the inclusion of such PPAs in the budget attest to the fact of its importance and urgency; and
Enhance the utilization of the 20 per cent of the IRA as prescribed in Department of Budget and Management-Department of Interior and Local Government (DBM-DILG) Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 2017-01.

We recommended the Management to:

Ensure that the specific guidelines for the implementation of projects funded by NGAs are complied with such as, but not limited to, the timing of publication or posting of the Invitation to Bid of the specific project or procurement opportunity;
Strictly monitor the implementation of the projects in order to avoid delayed implementation by the winning contractors. Diligently and timely call the attention of the concerned contractor in case of noted delays and take other necessary and appropriate actions, when warranted; 
Ensure strict compliance with the pertinent provisions of R.A. No. 9184 on the specific mode of procurement resorted to by the LGU;
Consider other available recourses of the LGU such as forfeiture of the performance security and enforcing liquidated damages to the previous contractor of Local Access Road Upgrading in Barangay Catioan, when warranted; and
Regularly revisit and evaluate the LGU’s compliance with the specific guidelines issued for projects funded by NGAs. In case of inadvertently overlooked non-compliance, ensure that necessary and appropriate actions are taken in accordance with the said guidelines.

We recommended that:

The LGU, primarily the Local Chief Executive (LCE) and the Local Poverty Reduction Action Team (LPRAT), as well as the Implementing Units concerned, re-evaluate the status of all the BUB/GPB projects with remaining unutilized funds coming from the different source agencies and from LGU counterpart. Such that:

For projects which had already been completed, take appropriate actions relating to the return of the balance of fund transfers to the source agencies in accordance with COA Circular No. 94-013 and, with regard to the savings relating to the LGU counterpart, ensure compliance with Section 418, Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) of Local Government Code (LGC) to enable the reversion of these funds to the GF;
For not yet fully implemented projects, strictly monitor and ensure its completion as soon as possible;
The concerned Implementing Units should ensure compliance with the Implementation Schedule of the projects submitted to the SA. Should there be issues encountered during the implementation warranting the departure from such Schedule (such as, but not limited to, unavailability of supply or need for supplemental funds), such issues should be resolved timely and should be properly documented through a catch-up plan for the determination of its reasonableness; and
The LGU, primarily the LCE and the LPRAT, as well as the Implementing Units concerned, should warrant the optimal utilization of funds received and the completion of all the BUB/GPB projects.

